KED\nCOMMIT: <sha>\nFILES_CHANGED: <list of modified/created files>\nTESTS_ADDED: <count>\nEXPORTS_ADDED: <new public functions, types, or components that other tasks may consume>\nCONCERNS: <anything unexpected, workarounds, or things the controller should know>\nSUMMARY: <1-2 sentences on what was built>\n```\n\n**Why EXPORTS_ADDED matters**: The controller uses this to build cross-task context. If Task 1 exports `getMsalInstance()` and Task 3 needs to import it, the controller must include that in Task 3's prompt.\n\n**2. Handle implementer status:**\n\n| Status | Action | Checkpoint write |\n|---|---|---|\n| **DONE** | → update checkpoint to `implemented` + commit SHA → proceed to spec review | Yes |\n| **DONE_WITH_CONCERNS** | Read concerns, assess if they affect correctness → update checkpoint to `implemented` | Yes |\n| **NEEDS_CONTEXT** | Provide missing context → re-dispatch (no state change) | No |\n| **BLOCKED** | Escalation ladder: (1) provide more context, (2) dispatch supplementary agent, (3) split task, (4) ask human | No (stays `dispatched`) |\n\n**3. Spec compliance review** (controller dispatches Opus subagent):\n\nThe controller dispatches a fresh spec compliance reviewer after the implementer reports DONE. This is an adversarial review — the reviewer independently verifies the implementation matches the spec.\n\nReviewer prompt (from `superpowers:subagent-driven-development/spec-reviewer-prompt.md`):\n- Provide: full task requirements + implementer's report + file paths to review\n- Reviewer reads actual code, compares to requirements line by line\n- Checks for: missing requirements, extra/unneeded work, misunderstandings\n- Does NOT trust the implementer's report — verifies independently\n\n| Result | Action |\n|---|---|\n| ✅ Spec compliant | → update checkpoint to `spec_reviewed` → proceed to quality review |\n| ❌ Issues found | → send findings back to implementer (same subagent via SendMessage) → implementer fixes → re-run spec review → repeat until ✅ |\n\n**4. Code quality review** (controller dispatches Opus subagent):\n\n**Only after spec compliance passes.** The controller dispatches a code quality reviewer using `superpowers:code-reviewer` template.\n\nProvide: diff (base SHA → current), task requirements, implementer's report.\n\nThe reviewer checks:\n- Each file has one clear responsibility with a well-defined interface\n- Units decomposed so they can be understood and tested independently\n- Implementation follows the file structure from the plan/spec\n- Clean, tested, maintainable code\n\n| Result | Action |\n|---|---|\n| ✅ Approved | → evaluate arch review trigger → proceed to arch review or post-task |\n| ❌ Issues (Critical/Important) | → implementer fixes → re-run quality review → repeat until ✅ |\n\n**5. Conditional per-task architecture review:**\n\nAfter quality review passes, evaluate whether this task's changes warrant a full `/architecture-review`. This catches domain-specific issues (security gaps, query performance, data isolation) that spec + quality reviewers don't target.\n\n**TRIGGER** — run per-task arch review if the task:\n- Touches security boundaries (auth, companyId, CSP, middleware, data isolation)\n- Adds or modifies database queries (Neo4j, Cypher)\n- Changes API routes or middleware\n- Modifies shared types or cross-cutting interfaces (schemas, service locator, repository base)\n\n**SKIP** — no per-task arch review if the task:\n- Is purely UI/component work with no data layer changes\n- Only adds or modifies tests\n- Is config, documentation, or styling only\n\nIf triggered:\n1. Controller invokes `/architecture-review` on the task's diff: `git diff {base-sha}..{task-commit-sha}`\n2. Use native Claude agents only (save `--mode both` for Step 4's cross-task review)\n3. **Auto-deploy**: Confirm persona selection immediately — per-task reviews are autonomous\n4. Fix all Critical + High findings: send back to implementer → fix → re-review → stop when 0 Critical + 0 High\n5. Update checkpoint to `arch_reviewed`\n\nIf skipped:\n- Update checkpoint directly to `arch_reviewed` (no review needed, noted in tracker)\n\n| Result | Action |\n|---|---|\n| Triggered + ✅ Pass | → update checkpoint to `arch_reviewed` → proceed to post-task |\n| Triggered + ❌ Findings | → implementer fixes → re-run arch review → repeat until 0 Critical + 0 High |\n| Skipped (low risk) | → update checkpoint to `arch_reviewed` (noted: \"skipped — UI only\" etc.) → proceed to post-task |\n\n**6. Post-task:**\n\n- Update Linear sub-issue status → \"Done\" (Linear plugin)\n- Update checkpoint task status → `done` with commit SHA\n- Run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/cleanup-vitest.sh`\n- Synthesize cross-task context for next task:\n  - `EXPORTS_ADDED` from implementer's report\n  - File paths modified\n  - Key design decisions (e.g., \"Task 1 used a singleton pattern for MSAL — follow that pattern\")\n\n#### 3d. Checkpoint Task Tracker\n\nThe controller updates the checkpoint after EVERY state transition (subagents never touch the checkpoint). Add this section to the checkpoint file:\n\n```markdown\n## Step 3: Implementation Task Tracker\n\n| Task | Linear ID | Status | Commit | Spec Review | Quality Review | Notes |\n|------|-----------|--------|--------|-------------|----------------|-------|\n| Task | Linear ID | Status | Commit | Spec Review | Quality Review | Arch Review | Notes |\n|------|-----------|--------|--------|-------------|----------------|-------------|-------|\n| 1. [name] | ZF0-xxx | done | abc123 | ✅ (1 round) | ✅ (1 round) | ✅ triggered (1 round) | API route |\n| 2. [name] | ZF0-xxx | arch_reviewed | def456 | ✅ (1 round) | ✅ (2 rounds) | skipped — UI only | — |\n| 3. [name] | ZF0-xxx | spec_reviewed | ghi789 | ✅ (1 round) | pending | — | — |\n| 4. [name] | ZF0-xxx | dispatched | — | — | — | — | Implementer working |\n| 5. [name] | ZF0-xxx | pending | — | — | — | — | Blocked by #3 |\n```\n\nTask states: `pending` → `dispatched` → `implemented` → `spec_reviewed` → `quality_reviewed` → `arch_reviewed` → `done`\n\n#### 3e. Recovery After Context Compaction\n\nIf context compacts mid-implementation, read the checkpoint task tracker and resume:\n\n| State found | Recovery action |\n|---|---|\n| `done` | Skip — move to next task |\n| `arch_reviewed` | Update Linear sub-issue, mark done |\n| `quality_reviewed` | Evaluate arch review trigger, dispatch if needed or mark arch_reviewed |\n| `spec_reviewed` | Dispatch code quality reviewer |\n| `implemented` | Dispatch spec compliance reviewer |\n| `dispatched` | Check `git log` — if commit exists for this task, mark implemented and dispatch spec review. If not, re-dispatch implementer. |\n| `pending` | Dispatch implementer |\n\n#### 3f. After All Sub-Tasks Complete\n\n1. Run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/cleanup-vitest.sh` — clear any leftover vitest processes\n2. Dispatch a **final code reviewer** (Opus, `superpowers:code-reviewer`) across the entire implementation diff (`git diff main...HEAD`) — catches cross-task issues that per-task reviews miss\n3. Run full test suite (`CI=true npx vitest run`): verify no cross-task regressions\n4. Update checkpoint: Step 3 complete\n\n#### 3g. Integration Wiring Check\n\nBefore proceeding to Phase 4, verify the cross-task wiring is correct. This catches issues that per-task reviews miss — each piece may be correct individually but fail when composed.\n\n1. Use LSP `incomingCalls`/`outgoingCalls` to trace the **full call chain** from entry point (API route or UI component) through every cross-task boundary to the data layer\n2. For each cross-task boundary (where Task A's output is Task B's input):\n   - Verify the import resolves (no missing exports)\n   - Verify function signatures match (no type mismatches at boundaries)\n   - Verify data shapes match (return type of A matches parameter type of B)\n3. Run `npx tsc --noEmit` — must pass clean\n4. If any wiring issue found → fix before proceeding\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Maintainability: N tests written, all behavioral, per-task spec + quality reviewed\n  Maintainability: cross-task wiring verified via LSP\n  Security: multi-tenancy isolation test ✓/✗\n  Experience: error handling tests ✓/✗, full call chain from entry point confirmed\n  Per-task: TDD ✓ + self-review ✓ + spec review ✓ + quality review ✓ for each sub-issue\n```\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → update task tracker after every state transition. After all tasks done, mark Step 3 complete → run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 3` → proceed only if exit 0.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4: REVIEW & HARDEN\n\n**Step 4: Architecture Review (cross-task integration)**\n\nEach task was individually verified by spec compliance + code quality reviewers in Step 3. This step focuses on **cross-task integration and architectural concerns**: do the pieces compose correctly? Are there coupling issues between tasks? Emergent behaviors from the combination? Architectural patterns that only emerge from the full diff? Do not re-review individual task correctness — that's covered by Step 3's two-stage review.\n\nInvoke `/architecture-review` on the diff with `--mode both` for maximum coverage.\n\nAlso dispatch in parallel:\n- `pr-review-toolkit:type-design-analyzer` — if the diff introduces new types/interfaces, review encapsulation and invariant quality\n- `pr-review-toolkit:pr-test-analyzer` — review test coverage quality and completeness across the full diff\n\n**Round 1**: Full persona panel (auto-selected from diff content)\n- Deploy all personas in parallel (clink + native)\n- Consolidate findings, dedup, rank by severity\n- **Enter plan mode** (`EnterPlanMode`) to organize fixes\n- Execute fixes\n\n**Decision gate after each round:**\n\n| Condition | Action |\n|---|---|\n| 0 Critical + 0 High | STOP → proceed to Step 5 |\n| Any Critical or High remaining | Next round |\n| Round 3 reached | STOP regardless — flag for human if unresolved |\n\n**Round 2** (if needed): Only re-deploy personas whose findings were fixed. Verify fixes, check for regressions. Plan mode for any new fixes.\n\n**Round 3** (hard cap): Fix remaining Critical/High. STOP regardless. If still unresolved after 3 rounds, the design needs rethinking — flag for human decision.\n\n**Early stop signals** (any round):\n- Findings are stylistic/preference, not correctness or security\n- Same issue described differently by multiple reviewers (noise)\n- Fixes adding more complexity than they remove\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  [all dimensions]: findings found → fixed → remaining\n  Review metadata: N rounds, personas used\n```\n\n**Step 5: Simplify**\n\nInvoke `/simplify`. Internally launches 3 parallel agents: Code Reuse Review, Code Quality Review, Efficiency Review. Fix actionable items.\n\nAlso dispatch `pr-review-toolkit:comment-analyzer` if the implementation added docstrings or comments — verify accuracy and prevent comment rot.\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Performance: efficiency findings [fixed/skipped]\n  Maintainability: reuse + quality [fixed/skipped]\n```\n\n**Step 6: Security Review + Sentry Hardening Validation**\n\nInvoke `/security-review`. This runs a focused vulnerability scan on the diff:\n1. Subagent identifies vulnerabilities\n2. Parallel subagents filter false positives\n3. Only high-confidence findings (≥ 8/10) reported\n\nAlso launch in parallel:\n- `silent-failure-hunter` subagent for error handling gaps\n- **Sentry hardening check** (only if `SENTRY_AVAILABLE = true` from Step 1) — cross-reference changed files against production error patterns:\n  1. Get list of changed files from `git diff --name-only main...HEAD`\n  2. Use Sentry MCP `search_issues` to query for issues mentioning those file paths or module names\n  3. Use `search_events` to find recent error events in the changed code paths\n  4. For each match: Does our change address the production error? Does it risk making it worse?\n  5. Flag any changed code path with active Sentry issues that we didn't harden\n\nThis catches what static analysis misses: \"you changed a function that throws 50 errors/day in production, but your change doesn't address the error pattern.\" If Sentry is not available, this sub-step is skipped — the security review and silent-failure-hunter still run.\n\nIf `--skip-review` was passed, skip Steps 4-6 entirely.\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Security: vulnerability findings (high-confidence only)\n  Security: Sentry production errors in changed paths [addressed/unaddressed/new-risk]\n  Experience: error handling coverage, silent failure gaps\n```\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → After EACH of Steps 4, 5, 6: Read checkpoint → append step section → write → run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} {step}` (use 4, 5, or 6 respectively). Include: architecture review rounds + outcomes, simplification results, security review findings, silent-failure-hunter results, Sentry hardening check results. Do NOT batch — update after each step completes.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 5: VERIFY\n\n**Steps 7+8: Preflight & E2E (SEQUENTIAL — memory optimization)**\n\nRun sequentially to avoid memory exhaustion (preflight vitest + Playwright E2E running simultaneously consumed ~8GB+ during ZF0-942):\n\n1. `/preflight full` — types, lint, test coverage, pattern scan, CI simulation, production build, actionlint\n2. Run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/cleanup-vitest.sh` — ensure preflight's vitest processes are gone\n3. `/e2e fast` — Playwright @fast-ci tests\n\n**Gate**: Both must pass. If either fails → fix and re-run from appropriate step.\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Maintainability: types ✓/✗, lint ✓/✗, coverage ✓/✗\n  Security: pattern scan ✓/✗\n  Experience: E2E N/N pass/fail\n  Performance: E2E timing baseline Δ\n```\n\n**Step 9: Success Criteria Verification**\n\nRe-fetch the Linear ticket (linear plugin). For each success criterion:\n- Map to specific code/test/behavior that satisfies it\n- Cite evidence (test name, code location, E2E test)\n\nInvoke `superpowers:verification-before-completion` — evidence before assertions.\n\n**Gate**: All criteria must be met. If any unmet → fix, re-run from Step 3.\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Experience: N/N success criteria verified with citations\n```\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → After Step 7: run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 7`. After Step 8: verify with step 8. After Step 9: verify with step 9. Include: preflight pass/fail, E2E results, success criteria verification with citations. Update after EACH sub-step, not batched.\n\n**Step 9.5: Manual Verification (CONDITIONAL)**\n\n**Trigger condition**: If ANY success criterion from Step 1 requires browser interaction, real external API responses, popup flows, OAuth/auth flows, or UI/UX confirmation that automated tests cannot verify — this step fires. If Step 9 mapped every criterion to automated evidence, skip to Step 10.\n\n**What happens**:\n1. Ensure dev server is running (`npm run dev:local`)\n2. Present a structured checklist derived from the success criteria that require manual verification:\n\n```\n── Step 9.5: Manual Verification ──────────────\n\nDev server: npm run dev:local (port 3000)\n\nVerify each criterion that requires manual testing:\n\n1. [criterion] → [specific URL/action to test]\n2. [criterion] → [specific URL/action to test]\n...\n\nReply with:\n  - \"verified\" → proceed to Ship Readiness\n  - \"issues: <description>\" → I'll fix and re-verify\n```\n\n3. **BLOCK** — wait for human response. Do not proceed until the user replies.\n4. If \"issues\" → fix → re-run from the appropriate step → re-verify\n5. If \"verified\" → proceed to Step 10\n\n**Why this exists**: During ZF0-942, 6 integration bugs (MSAL popup timing, callback page compilation delay, Graph API annotation stripping) were only discoverable by running the real app. Automated tests mocked these boundaries. This step catches what mocks can't.\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → If Step 9.5 fired: run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 9.5`. Include: which criteria were manually verified, human's response.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 6: SHIP READINESS\n\n**Step 10: Dimensional Impact Assessment**\n\nThis is the synthesis step. Get the complete diff: `git diff main...HEAD`\n\n**Pre-assessment: Sentry Production Baseline** (only if `SENTRY_AVAILABLE = true` from Step 1)\n\nBefore launching assessment agents, establish the production health baseline for the code area being shipped into:\n1. Use Sentry MCP `search_issues` for all changed files/modules — get current error rates, affected user counts\n2. Use Sentry MCP `search_events` for recent error events in the changed code paths — get error frequency trends\n3. Compile into a production baseline snapshot:\n   - Current error rate in affected area (events/day)\n   - Users affected by existing issues\n   - Top error patterns (types, frequencies)\n   - Trend direction (improving, stable, degrading)\n\nIf Sentry is not available, skip this pre-assessment — the assessment agents run with LSP + accumulated evidence only (the pipeline operated this way before Sentry integration and remains fully functional without it).\n\nLaunch two parallel subagents with the full diff + all accumulated evidence from Steps 1-9 + Sentry production baseline (if available):\n\n**Agent A (Performance + Security)** — use `performance-optimizer` or `neo4j-specialist`:\n\nFor each changed function/query in the diff:\n1. Use LSP `incomingCalls` to trace upstream callers → hot path detection\n2. Use LSP `outgoingCalls` to trace downstream dependencies\n3. Use LSP `findReferences` to find all consumers of changed interfaces\n\nEvaluate against universal baseline + task-specific criteria + accumulated evidence + Sentry baseline.\n\n- Performance: Is this on a hot path? New DB queries safe? Loops with I/O? Unbounded results? Sentry shows existing perf-related errors?\n- Security: companyId from auth on all paths? isDeleted filtered? User input reaches queries? Internal state exposed? Sentry shows data exposure patterns?\n\n**Agent B (Experience + Maintainability)** — use `code-review-expert`:\n\nFor each changed component/function:\n1. Use LSP `incomingCalls` / `findReferences` to trace user-facing effects\n2. Verify test coverage of changes\n3. Check coupling and dependency changes\n\nEvaluate against universal baseline + task-specific criteria + accumulated evidence + Sentry baseline.\n\n- Experience: Backward compatible? Errors handled? Loading states? Consumer handling? Sentry shows user-facing errors that change should address?\n- Maintainability: Every behavior tested? Type-safe? Follows patterns? Coupling? Sentry shows recurring errors suggesting missing test coverage?\n\nSynthesize into Ship Readiness Report (see `references/ship-readiness-template.md`). Include a **PRODUCTION CONTEXT** section in the report with the Sentry baseline and how the change relates to it.\n\n**Gate**: Human reviews report. Confirms SHIP or requests fixes. If fixes needed → re-run from appropriate step, then re-run Step 10 on updated diff.\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → Read checkpoint → append Step 10 section (full ship readiness report, dimensional ratings, Sentry production baseline if available, human SHIP/FIX decision) → write → run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 10` → proceed only if exit 0.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 7: DELIVER\n\n**Step 11: Commit & PR**\n\n1. Invoke `superpowers:finishing-a-development-branch`\n2. Invoke `/commit-commands:commit-push-pr`\n3. Include ship readiness report in PR body\n4. Update Linear issue status to \"In Review\" (linear plugin)\n\n**Step 12: Copilot Review Response**\n\nAfter pushing, Copilot automatically reviews the PR.\n\n1. Wait for Copilot review to appear\n2. Fetch comments via GitHub plugin (`pull_request_read`, PR comments API)\n3. Invoke `superpowers:receiving-code-review` — technical rigor when processing feedback; don't blindly agree with suggestions\n\nFor each Copilot comment:\n- Assess validity — is this a real issue or noise?\n- If valid → fix, push\n- If invalid → reply with technical reasoning why it's not applicable\n- Reply to each comment with commit ref + explanation\n\nIf substantive fixes were pushed:\n- Quick re-run of Step 10 on updated diff (only affected dimensions)\n- Push, reply to comments\n\nUpdate Linear issue status to \"Done\" (linear plugin).\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → After Step 11: run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 11`. After Step 12: verify with step 12. Include: PR URL, commit SHAs, Copilot review responses, Linear status update, final outcome.\n\n---\n\n## Resume Protocol\n\nWhen a conversation resumes after context compaction (or in a new session), use this protocol to recover pipeline state:\n\n1. **Read the checkpoint file**: `cat thoughts/shared/ship-task/checkpoints/{ticket-id}-checkpoint.md`\n2. **Extract from frontmatter**: `step` (last completed), `substep` (if mid-step), `branch`, `plan`, `spec`\n3. **Extract from Gates section**: `SENTRY_AVAILABLE` and any other gate values\n4. **Read the plan file** (from frontmatter `plan` path) to understand task structure\n5. **Read through all step sections** to rebuild accumulated evidence and understand decisions made\n6. **Check git state**: Verify you're on the correct branch, review `git log --oneline main..HEAD` for commits made so far\n7. **Determine resume point**:\n   - If `substep` is empty → resume from step N+1\n   - If `substep` starts with `task-` (mid-Step-3) → read the task tracker table, resume per 3e recovery rules\n   - If `substep` starts with `step-` (mid-Phase-4) → resume at the next incomplete step (e.g., `step-4-complete` → resume at Step 5)\n8. **Cross-reference with Linear**: `list_issues parentId=<ticket-id>` → verify sub-issue statuses match checkpoint task tracker\n\n**Critical state to recover:**\n- `SENTRY_AVAILABLE` gate — determines whether Sentry sub-steps run in Steps 6 and 10\n- Branch name — ensures you're on the right branch\n- All step sections — contain accumulated evidence that feeds into subsequent quality gates\n- **Task tracker table** (from Step 3 section) — per-task states (pending/dispatched/implemented/spec_reviewed/quality_reviewed/arch_reviewed/done) with commit SHAs and review results. Determines which tasks need which review stage.\n- **Linear sub-issue statuses** — `list_issues parentId=<ticket-id>` shows completion status for each sub-task. Cross-reference with checkpoint tracker for consistency.\n- **Git log** — `git log --oneline main..HEAD` shows which task commits exist. Ground truth for what's been implemented.\n\n**Example resume flow:**\n```\nCheckpoint: ZF0-876-checkpoint.md → step: 3\n→ Read: branch = \"zf0-876\", SENTRY_AVAILABLE = false\n→ Read Step 1-3 sections for accumulated evidence\n→ git checkout zf0-876\n→ Resume at Step 4 (Architecture Review)\n```\n\n---\n\n## LSP Integration\n\nThe TypeScript LSP is the primary tool for downstream effect tracing in Step 10. Use it over Grep for accuracy — LSP gives the actual compiler-verified call graph, not text matches.\n\n| Operation | Use |\n|---|---|\n| `incomingCalls` | Who calls this changed function? (hot path detection) |\n| `outgoingCalls` | What does this function call? (dependency tracing) |\n| `findReferences` | Where is this changed type/interface used? |\n| `goToDefinition` | Resolve actual types (Step 3, implementation) |\n| `goToImplementation` | Find concrete implementations of changed interfaces |\n| `hover` | Check type signatures inline |\n\nUse LSP as primary, Grep as fallback for non-TS references (Cypher queries, config, dynamic calls).\n\n---\n\n## Parallel Execution Map\n\n```\nSequential: Step 1 → Step 2 → Step 3 (3a→3c→3f→3g) → Step 4 → Step 5 → Step 6\n                                                                                │\nSequential:                                                          Step 7 → Step 8\n                   