          "text": "Base directory for this skill: /Users/derricklee/.claude/skills/ship-task\n\n# Ship Task — Full Lifecycle Pipeline\n\nOrchestrates the complete journey from Linear ticket to merged PR. Every step builds evidence toward a dimensional quality assessment across Performance, Security, Experience, and Maintainability.\n\n## Arguments\n\n```\n/ship-task <ticket-id> [--skip-review]\n```\n\n- `<ticket-id>`: Linear issue ID (e.g., ZF0-810) — required\n- `--skip-review`: Skip architecture + security review (only for docs/config-only changes)\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Dimensional Assessment\n\nFour quality dimensions are evaluated throughout the pipeline. Evidence accumulates in conversation context — each step adds findings, and the final assessment synthesizes everything.\n\n- **Performance**: Hot paths, query efficiency, N+1 patterns, concurrency\n- **Security**: Tenant isolation, auth chains, input validation, data exposure\n- **Experience**: Backward compatibility, error handling, success criteria\n- **Maintainability**: Test coverage, type safety, patterns, coupling\n\n### Criteria: Universal Baseline + Task-Specific\n\nUniversal baseline criteria always apply (see `references/dimensional-criteria.md`). On top of that, Step 1 derives task-specific criteria from the ticket content — e.g., a ticket mentioning \"Cypher query\" adds Neo4j-specific performance criteria.\n\nThis approach needs zero maintenance: universal principles don't change, and task-specific criteria are derived fresh each time.\n\n### Checkpoint Persistence (Write-Through)\n\nThe pipeline survives context compaction via a **single checkpoint file per ticket**, updated after every step. This is a write-through strategy: persist state *as it's generated*, not at phase boundaries. Context compaction can happen at any time with no warning — if you wait until a phase ends to write, the evidence from that phase may already be compacted.\n\n**Directory**: `thoughts/shared/ship-task/checkpoints/`\n\n**Naming**: `{ticket-id}-checkpoint.md` — one file per ticket, updated incrementally.\n\n**Read cadence**: Re-read the checkpoint file **at the start of every step** if you don't have its contents in your current context. Context compaction can happen between any two steps — never assume you remember what the checkpoint says. If in doubt, read it.\n\n**Write cadence**: Update the checkpoint file **after every step that produces evidence** and **after every state transition within Step 3**. Each update appends the new step's state to the existing file. Read the file before updating to preserve prior content.\n\n**Checkpoint file format:**\n\n```markdown\n---\nticket: {ticket-id}\nstep: {last-completed-step-number}\nsubstep: {for Step 3: \"task-N-STATE\", for Steps 4-6: \"step-N-complete\". Omit if step is fully complete.}\nbranch: {git-branch-name}\nplan: {path to implementation plan}\nspec: {path to design spec}\nlinear-url: {linear-issue-url}\ntimestamp: {ISO-8601 of last update}\n---\n\n## Gates\n\nSENTRY_AVAILABLE: {true/false}\n{other gates as discovered}\n\n## Step 1: Context\n{ticket summary, success criteria, task-specific criteria, Sentry baseline}\n\n## Step 2: Plan\n{path taken (A/B), research synthesis, sub-issue IDs, plan path if Path B}\n\n## Step 3: Implement\n{plan path, spec path}\n\n### Task Tracker\n| Task | Linear ID | Status | Commit | Notes |\n|------|-----------|--------|--------|-------|\n| 1. [name] | ZF0-xxx | {pending/dispatched/implemented/spec_reviewed/quality_reviewed/arch_reviewed/done} | {sha} | {notes} |\n\n## Step 4: Architecture Review\n{rounds, findings fixed/remaining}\n\n## Step 5: Simplify\n{findings fixed/skipped}\n\n## Step 6: Security Review\n{vulnerability findings, silent-failure-hunter results, Sentry hardening}\n\n## Steps 7+8: Preflight & E2E\n{pass/fail, test counts}\n\n## Step 9: Success Criteria\n{N/N verified with citations}\n\n## Step 10: Ship Readiness\n{dimensional ratings, full report}\n\n## Step 11: Commit & PR\n{PR URL, commit SHAs}\n\n## Step 12: Copilot Review\n{comments addressed, final status}\n\n## Evidence Accumulated\n\n### Performance\n{cumulative evidence}\n\n### Security\n{cumulative evidence}\n\n### Experience\n{cumulative evidence}\n\n### Maintainability\n{cumulative evidence}\n```\n\n**Write instructions — ENFORCED via script:**\n\nAfter completing each step, execute this exact sequence (no shortcuts):\n\n1. `Read` the checkpoint file → preserve all existing content\n2. Append the new step's section to the content\n3. Update `step:` and `timestamp:` in frontmatter\n4. `Write` the updated file\n5. Run: `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {ticket-id} {step-number}`\n6. **If verify exits non-zero → STOP. Fix the checkpoint before proceeding.**\n7. Only after verify passes → proceed to next step\n\nThis is non-negotiable. The ZF0-942 retro showed that text instructions alone (\"treat it like a write-ahead log\") are insufficient — the checkpoint stopped being updated after Step 3. The verify script enforces discipline by failing loudly when the checkpoint doesn't match expected state.\n\n**Pre-step read (every step):** At the START of every step, `Read` the checkpoint file. If context compacted, this rebuilds your understanding. If the previous step's write was skipped, you'll see the mismatch and can fix it before proceeding.\n\n---\n\n## Pipeline\n\n### Step 0: Check for Existing Checkpoint\n\nBefore starting the pipeline, check if a checkpoint already exists for this ticket:\n\n```bash\ncat thoughts/shared/ship-task/checkpoints/{ticket-id}-checkpoint.md 2>/dev/null\n```\n\n**If checkpoint exists:** Follow the **Resume Protocol** (see below) instead of starting from Step 1. Read the checkpoint to determine the last completed step, then resume from the next one.\n\n**If no checkpoint exists:** Proceed to Step 1 as normal.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 1: CONTEXT\n\n**Step 1: Load Context + Derive Criteria**\n\n1. Invoke `/start-task <ticket-id>` — loads Linear issue, creates branch\n2. Extract success criteria from the ticket → these become Experience verification targets\n3. Parse ticket content → derive task-specific dimensional criteria on top of universal baseline (see `references/dimensional-criteria.md` for derivation rules)\n4. **Sentry Production Context** (conditional — probe and gate):\n   - **Probe**: Attempt a single Sentry MCP `find_organizations` or `find_projects` call\n   - If Sentry MCP is unavailable (no server configured, auth fails, no project found) → set `SENTRY_AVAILABLE = false`, skip all Sentry steps in the pipeline (Steps 1, 6, 10), log: \"Sentry not available — pipeline continues without production context\"\n   - If available → set `SENTRY_AVAILABLE = true`, then:\n     - Use Sentry MCP `search_issues` to find recent production issues related to the ticket's affected modules/files\n     - Use `sentry:issue-summarizer` agent if multiple issues found — get user impact, error patterns, root causes\n     - Record: error counts, affected users, top issues, recurring error patterns\n     - If Sentry surfaces active production issues in the affected area:\n       - Elevate relevant dimensional criteria (Performance if high error rate, Security if data exposure patterns)\n       - Note whether ticket scope should expand to address related production issues — flag for human decision in Step 2\n5. Seed evidence with baseline + task-specific criteria + Sentry production context (if available)\n\n```\nEvidence seeded:\n  Experience: N success criteria identified\n  Sentry: AVAILABLE / NOT AVAILABLE (gates Steps 6 and 10 Sentry sub-steps)\n  Performance: Sentry error rate in affected area (baseline) — or \"no production data\"\n  Security: Sentry data exposure patterns (if any) — or \"no production data\"\n  + task-specific criteria derived from ticket content\n  + production context from Sentry (N active issues, M affected users) — if available\n```\n\nTools: `/start-task`, Linear plugin, GitHub plugin, Sentry MCP (`find_projects`, `search_issues`, `get_issue_details`), `sentry:issue-summarizer`\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → Read checkpoint → append Step 1 section (ticket summary, success criteria, branch name, `SENTRY_AVAILABLE`, task-specific criteria, Sentry production context) → write → run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 1` → proceed only if exit 0.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2: PLAN\n\n**Step 2: Research & Plan (Adaptive)**\n\nThis step adapts based on how much detail the Linear ticket already has. Linear is the source of truth for task tracking — all tasks must exist as Linear sub-issues before execution begins.\n\n#### 2a. Assess Linear Sub-Issues\n\nFetch sub-issues: `list_issues parentId=<ticket-id>`\n\n**DECISION GATE:**\n\n| Condition | Path |\n|---|---|\n| Sub-issues exist with implementation detail (file refs, steps, acceptance criteria) | **Path A: Research Only** |\n| No sub-issues, OR sub-issues are stubs (title only, no detail) | **Path B: Plan & Create Sub-Issues** |\n\n#### Path A: Research Only (Sub-Issues Already Exist)\n\nThe Linear sub-issues ARE the task specs. Research enriches them with codebase context for the implementer.\n\n1. Launch parallel research subagents:\n   - `feature-dev:code-explorer` — trace affected code paths, identify hot paths and tenant boundaries\n   - `feature-dev:code-architect` — validate implementation approach against codebase\n   - `codebase-pattern-finder` — find existing patterns the implementer should follow\n\n2. Optional (as needed):\n   - `neo4j-specialist` — graph modeling decisions\n   - `context7` plugin — library docs for new dependencies\n   - `web-search-researcher` — novel approaches\n\n3. For each sub-issue, build an **implementer context bundle**:\n   - Exact file paths to create/modify (from research)\n   - Relevant code snippets showing patterns to follow\n   - Type definitions the implementer will need\n   - Dependencies on other sub-issues\n\n4. Record research synthesis in checkpoint. No plan file needed — Linear is the plan.\n\n#### Path B: Plan & Create Sub-Issues (High-Level Ticket)\n\nThe ticket needs decomposition into concrete tasks.\n\n1. (Optional) Invoke `superpowers:brainstorming` if approach is uncertain — multiple valid architectures, unfamiliar domain, or significant trade-offs. Skip for straightforward tickets.\n\n2. Launch parallel research subagents (same as Path A above).\n\n3. Invoke `superpowers:writing-plans` for the implementation plan.\n   - **Important**: writing-plans will offer an execution handoff (\"Subagent-Driven or Inline?\") at the end. **Decline the handoff** — ship-task owns execution via Step 3. Say: \"Plan only — I'll handle execution.\"\n\n4. Convert plan tasks → Linear sub-issues:\n   - Create each plan task as a sub-issue under the parent ticket (Linear plugin `save_issue` with `parentId`)\n   - Set `blockedBy`/`blocks` relations based on plan task dependencies\n   - Include full task description, implementation steps, file references, and acceptance criteria in the sub-issue body\n   - Record Linear sub-issue IDs in checkpoint\n\n5. Wait for human confirmation of the plan before proceeding.\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Performance: hot paths mapped\n  Security: tenant boundaries identified\n  Maintainability: existing patterns cataloged\n  Plan: [Path A: research context bundles per sub-issue / Path B: plan file + Linear sub-issues created]\n```\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → Read checkpoint → append Step 2 section (path taken, research synthesis, sub-issue IDs, plan path if Path B) → write → run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 2` → proceed only if exit 0.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3: IMPLEMENT (Subagent-Driven)\n\n**Step 3: Sequential Implementation with Two-Stage Review**\n\nImplementation follows the `superpowers:subagent-driven-development` pattern: fresh Opus subagent per task, sequential execution, two-stage review (spec compliance → code quality). The controller (main agent) orchestrates; subagents do the work.\n\n#### 3a. Derive Execution Order from Linear\n\n1. Fetch sub-issues: `list_issues parentId=<ticket-id>`\n2. For each sub-issue, read `blockedBy` and `blocks` relations (use `get_issue` with `includeRelations: true`)\n3. Order tasks: resolve dependency graph into a sequential execution order. Tasks with no `blockedBy` come first; dependent tasks follow their prerequisites.\n4. If no sub-issues exist at this point, STOP — Step 2 should have created them (Path B) or they should already exist (Path A). If missing, re-run Step 2.\n\n#### 3b. Supplementary Subagents\n\nAvailable at any point during Step 3 — controller dispatches as needed:\n\n- `codebase-pattern-finder` — before dispatching an implementer, find existing patterns. Paste relevant snippets into the implementer prompt.\n- `feature-dev:code-explorer` — trace execution paths for complex tasks before implementation.\n- `test-strategist` — when test design is complex (Shadow DOM mocking, async events, capture-phase testing).\n- `superpowers:systematic-debugging` — when implementer reports BLOCKED with failing tests.\n- `feature-dev:code-architect` — when implementer reports BLOCKED due to architectural ambiguity.\n- `pr-review-toolkit:code-simplifier` — after quality review passes and before marking done, simplify code >10 lines of logic.\n\n#### 3c. Per-Task Cycle\n\nExecute tasks sequentially in dependency order. For each task:\n\n**Before each task: update checkpoint** → mark task as `dispatched` in the tracker table. This happens BEFORE dispatching so that compaction mid-dispatch can recover.\n\n**1. Dispatch implementer subagent (Opus, fresh context):**\n\nUse the implementer prompt pattern from `superpowers:subagent-driven-development`. Paste the full task text into the prompt (don't make the subagent read files). Include:\n- Full task description from Linear sub-issue + research context bundle from Step 2 (or plan task text if Path B)\n- Cross-task context: what prior tasks built, exports available, files modified, key design decisions\n- \"Ask questions before starting — it's always OK to pause and clarify\"\n- Escalation protocol: \"If stuck, report BLOCKED or NEEDS_CONTEXT — don't guess\"\n- \"If tests fail unexpectedly, use `superpowers:systematic-debugging` before guessing at fixes\"\n\n**TDD cycle** (from `superpowers:test-driven-development`):\n- \"Follow strict TDD for each unit of work:\"\n  1. Write the failing test\n  2. Run it — verify it fails for the right reason\n  3. Write minimal code to make the test pass\n  4. Run it — verify it passes\n  5. Refactor — invoke `pr-review-toolkit:code-simplifier` if the implementation exceeds 10 lines of logic\n- \"Do NOT write implementation before writing the test\"\n\n**TypeScript LSP** — the implementer should use LSP tools for type-safe implementation:\n- `goToDefinition` — resolve actual types before using them\n- `hover` — check type signatures inline\n- `findReferences` — verify no callers break when changing interfaces\n- `incomingCalls` / `outgoingCalls` — trace call graph for impact analysis\n\n**Vitest constraints** (prevent memory exhaustion):\n- \"Run ONLY the specific test file you're working on: `npx vitest run path/to/your.test.ts --poolOptions.threads.maxThreads=1`\"\n- \"NEVER run bare `vitest` (starts watch mode) or `vitest run` without a file path (runs full suite)\"\n- \"Before reporting back, run: `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/cleanup-vitest.sh`\"\n\n**Implementer self-review + structured report** (before reporting back):\n- \"After TDD cycle completes, perform a self-review, then report using this exact format:\"\n  1. Spec check: re-read the task description — did you build exactly what was asked? Anything missing or extra?\n  2. Run `npx tsc --noEmit` on your changed files — must be clean\n  3. Run `npx eslint <changed-files> --quiet` — must be clean\n  4. Report using this structure:\n\n```\nSTATUS: DONE | DONE_WITH_CONCERNS | NEEDS_CONTEXT | BLOCKED\nCOMMIT: <sha>\nFILES_CHANGED: <list of modified/created files>\nTESTS_ADDED: <count>\nEXPORTS_ADDED: <new public functions, types, or components that other tasks may consume>\nCONCERNS: <anything unexpected, workarounds, or things the controller should know>\nSUMMARY: <1-2 sentences on what was built>\n```\n\n**Why EXPORTS_ADDED matters**: The controller uses this to build cross-task context. If Task 1 exports `getMsalInstance()` and Task 3 needs to import it, the controller must include that in Task 3's prompt.\n\n**2. Handle implementer status:**\n\n| Status | Action | Checkpoint write |\n|---|---|---|\n| **DONE** | → update checkpoint to `implemented` + commit SHA → proceed to spec review | Yes |\n| **DONE_WITH_CONCERNS** | Read concerns, assess if they affect correctness → update checkpoint to `implemented` | Yes |\n| **NEEDS_CONTEXT** | Provide missing context → re-dispatch (no state change) | No |\n| **BLOCKED** | Escalation ladder: (1) provide more context, (2) dispatch supplementary agent, (3) split task, (4) ask human | No (stays `dispatched`) |\n\n**3. Spec compliance review** (controller dispatches Opus subagent):\n\nThe controller dispatches a fresh spec compliance reviewer after the implementer reports DONE. This is an adversarial review — the reviewer independently verifies the implementation matches the spec.\n\nReviewer prompt (from `superpowers:subagent-driven-development/spec-reviewer-prompt.md`):\n- Provide: full task requirements + implementer's report + file paths to review\n- Reviewer reads actual code, compares to requirements line by line\n- Checks for: missing requirements, extra/unneeded work, misunderstandings\n- Does NOT trust the implementer's report — verifies independently\n\n| Result | Action |\n|---|---|\n| ✅ Spec compliant | → update checkpoint to `spec_reviewed` → proceed to quality review |\n| ❌ Issues found | → send findings back to implementer (same subagent via SendMessage) → implementer fixes → re-run spec review → repeat until ✅ |\n\n**4. Code quality review** (controller dispatches Opus subagent):\n\n**Only after spec compliance passes.** The controller dispatches a code quality reviewer using `superpowers:code-reviewer` template.\n\nProvide: diff (base SHA → current), task requirements, implementer's report.\n\nThe reviewer checks:\n- Each file has one clear responsibility with a well-defined interface\n- Units decomposed so they can be understood and tested independently\n- Implementation follows the file structure from the plan/spec\n- Clean, tested, maintainable code\n\n| Result | Action |\n|---|---|\n| ✅ Approved | → evaluate arch review trigger → proceed to arch review or post-task |\n| ❌ Issues (Critical/Important) | → implementer fixes → re-run quality review → repeat until ✅ |\n\n**5. Conditional per-task architecture review:**\n\nAfter quality review passes, evaluate whether this task's changes warrant a full `/architecture-review`. This catches domain-specific issues (security gaps, query performance, data isolation) that spec + quality reviewers don't target.\n\n**TRIGGER** — run per-task arch review if the task:\n- Touches security boundaries (auth, companyId, CSP, middleware, data isolation)\n- Adds or modifies database queries (Neo4j, Cypher)\n- Changes API routes or middleware\n- Modifies shared types or cross-cutting interfaces (schemas, service locator, repository base)\n\n**SKIP** — no per-task arch review if the task:\n- Is purely UI/component work with no data layer changes\n- Only adds or modifies tests\n- Is config, documentation, or styling only\n\nIf triggered:\n1. Controller invokes `/architecture-review` on the task's diff: `git diff {base-sha}..{task-commit-sha}`\n2. Use native Claude agents only (save `--mode both` for Step 4's cross-task review)\n3. **Auto-deploy**: Confirm persona selection immediately — per-task reviews are autonomous\n4. Fix all Critical + High findings: send back to implementer → fix → re-review → stop when 0 Critical + 0 High\n5. Update checkpoint to `arch_reviewed`\n\nIf skipped:\n- Update checkpoint directly to `arch_reviewed` (no review needed, noted in tracker)\n\n| Result | Action |\n|---|---|\n| Triggered + ✅ Pass | → update checkpoint to `arch_reviewed` → proceed to post-task |\n| Triggered + ❌ Findings | → implementer fixes → re-run arch review → repeat until 0 Critical + 0 High |\n| Skipped (low risk) | → update checkpoint to `arch_reviewed` (noted: \"skipped — UI only\" etc.) → proceed to post-task |\n\n**6. Post-task:**\n\n- Update Linear sub-issue status → \"Done\" (Linear plugin)\n- Update checkpoint task status → `done` with commit SHA\n- Run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/cleanup-vitest.sh`\n- Synthesize cross-task context for next task:\n  - `EXPORTS_ADDED` from implementer's report\n  - File paths modified\n  - Key design decisions (e.g., \"Task 1 used a singleton pattern for MSAL — follow that pattern\")\n\n#### 3d. Checkpoint Task Tracker\n\nThe controller updates the checkpoint after EVERY state transition (subagents never touch the checkpoint). Add this section to the checkpoint file:\n\n```markdown\n## Step 3: Implementation Task Tracker\n\n| Task | Linear ID | Status | Commit | Spec Review | Quality Review | Notes |\n|------|-----------|--------|--------|-------------|----------------|-------|\n| Task | Linear ID | Status | Commit | Spec Review | Quality Review | Arch Review | Notes |\n|------|-----------|--------|--------|-------------|----------------|-------------|-------|\n| 1. [name] | ZF0-xxx | done | abc123 | ✅ (1 round) | ✅ (1 round) | ✅ triggered (1 round) | API route |\n| 2. [name] | ZF0-xxx | arch_reviewed | def456 | ✅ (1 round) | ✅ (2 rounds) | skipped — UI only | — |\n| 3. [name] | ZF0-xxx | spec_reviewed | ghi789 | ✅ (1 round) | pending | — | — |\n| 4. [name] | ZF0-xxx | dispatched | — | — | — | — | Implementer working |\n| 5. [name] | ZF0-xxx | pending | — | — | — | — | Blocked by #3 |\n```\n\nTask states: `pending` → `dispatched` → `implemented` → `spec_reviewed` → `quality_reviewed` → `arch_reviewed` → `done`\n\n#### 3e. Recovery After Context Compaction\n\nIf context compacts mid-implementation, read the checkpoint task tracker and resume:\n\n| State found | Recovery action |\n|---|---|\n| `done` | Skip — move to next task |\n| `arch_reviewed` | Update Linear sub-issue, mark done |\n| `quality_reviewed` | Evaluate arch review trigger, dispatch if needed or mark arch_reviewed |\n| `spec_reviewed` | Dispatch code quality reviewer |\n| `implemented` | Dispatch spec compliance reviewer |\n| `dispatched` | Check `git log` — if commit exists for this task, mark implemented and dispatch spec review. If not, re-dispatch implementer. |\n| `pending` | Dispatch implementer |\n\n#### 3f. After All Sub-Tasks Complete\n\n1. Run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/cleanup-vitest.sh` — clear any leftover vitest processes\n2. Dispatch a **final code reviewer** (Opus, `superpowers:code-reviewer`) across the entire implementation diff (`git diff main...HEAD`) — catches cross-task issues that per-task reviews miss\n3. Run full test suite (`CI=true npx vitest run`): verify no cross-task regressions\n4. Update checkpoint: Step 3 complete\n\n#### 3g. Integration Wiring Check\n\nBefore proceeding to Phase 4, verify the cross-task wiring is correct. This catches issues that per-task reviews miss — each piece may be correct individually but fail when composed.\n\n1. Use LSP `incomingCalls`/`outgoingCalls` to trace the **full call chain** from entry point (API route or UI component) through every cross-task boundary to the data layer\n2. For each cross-task boundary (where Task A's output is Task B's input):\n   - Verify the import resolves (no missing exports)\n   - Verify function signatures match (no type mismatches at boundaries)\n   - Verify data shapes match (return type of A matches parameter type of B)\n3. Run `npx tsc --noEmit` — must pass clean\n4. If any wiring issue found → fix before proceeding\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Maintainability: N tests written, all behavioral, per-task spec + quality reviewed\n  Maintainability: cross-task wiring verified via LSP\n  Security: multi-tenancy isolation test ✓/✗\n  Experience: error handling tests ✓/✗, full call chain from entry point confirmed\n  Per-task: TDD ✓ + self-review ✓ + spec review ✓ + quality review ✓ for each sub-issue\n```\n\n**📌 CHECKPOINT GATE** → update task tracker after every state transition. After all tasks done, mark Step 3 complete → run `~/.claude/scripts/ship-task/verify-checkpoint.sh {id} 3` → proceed only if exit 0.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4: REVIEW & HARDEN\n\n**Step 4: Architecture Review (cross-task integration)**\n\nEach task was individually verified by spec compliance + code quality reviewers in Step 3. This step focuses on **cross-task integration and architectural concerns**: do the pieces compose correctly? Are there coupling issues between tasks? Emergent behaviors from the combination? Architectural patterns that only emerge from the full diff? Do not re-review individual task correctness — that's covered by Step 3's two-stage review.\n\nInvoke `/architecture-review` on the diff with `--mode both` for maximum coverage.\n\nAlso dispatch in parallel:\n- `pr-review-toolkit:type-design-analyzer` — if the diff introduces new types/interfaces, review encapsulation and invariant quality\n- `pr-review-toolkit:pr-test-analyzer` — review test coverage quality and completeness across the full diff\n\n**Round 1**: Full persona panel (auto-selected from diff content)\n- Deploy all personas in parallel (clink + native)\n- Consolidate findings, dedup, rank by severity\n- **Enter plan mode** (`EnterPlanMode`) to organize fixes\n- Execute fixes\n\n**Decision gate after each round:**\n\n| Condition | Action |\n|---|---|\n| 0 Critical + 0 High | STOP → proceed to Step 5 |\n| Any Critical or High remaining | Next round |\n| Round 3 reached | STOP regardless — flag for human if unresolved |\n\n**Round 2** (if needed): Only re-deploy personas whose findings were fixed. Verify fixes, check for regressions. Plan mode for any new fixes.\n\n**Round 3** (hard cap): Fix remaining Critical/High. STOP regardless. If still unresolved after 3 rounds, the design needs rethinking — flag for human decision.\n\n**Early stop signals** (any round):\n- Findings are stylistic/preference, not correctness or security\n- Same issue described differently by multiple reviewers (noise)\n- Fixes adding more complexity than they remove\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  [all dimensions]: findings found → fixed → remaining\n  Review metadata: N rounds, personas used\n```\n\n**Step 5: Simplify**\n\nInvoke `/simplify`. Internally launches 3 parallel agents: Code Reuse Review, Code Quality Review, Efficiency Review. Fix actionable items.\n\nAlso dispatch `pr-review-toolkit:comment-analyzer` if the implementation added docstrings or comments — verify accuracy and prevent comment rot.\n\n```\nEvidence accumulated:\n  Performance: efficiency findings [fixed/skipped]\n  Maintainability: reuse + quality [fixed/skipped]\n```\n\n**Step 6: Security Review + Sentry Hardening Validation**\n\nInvoke `/security-review`. This runs a focused vulnerability scan on the diff:\n1. Subagent identifies vulnerabilities\n2. Parallel subagents filter false positives\n3. Only high-confidence findings (≥ 8/10) reported\n\nAlso launch in parallel:\n- `silent-failure-hunter` subagent for error handling gaps\n- **Sentry hardening check** (only if `SENTRY_AVAILABLE = true` from Step 1) — cross-reference changed files against production error patterns:\n  1. Get list of changed files from `git diff --name-only main...HEAD`\n  2. Use Sentry MCP `search_issues` to query for issues mentioning those file paths or module names\n  3. Use `search_events` to find recent error events in the changed code paths\n  4. For each match: Does our change address the production error? Does it risk making it worse?\n  5. Flag any changed code path with active Sentry issues that